record.title: Consider an improved Python Base Image for Docker Meltano Images
record.description:
### Problem to solve
Reducing security vulnerabilities in Meltano Docker Images to meet IT Security Guidelines.


### Target audience
This will be beneficial for all Meltano Users who use the Meltano Docker Images - especially helpful for Containerized implementations of Meltano.


### Further details
When scanning the Meltano Image for vulnerabilities (via AWS Container Registry - ECR), there are many security vulnerabilities listed. They mainly appear to be attributed to the Docker Python base image.

My security team would like to minimize the number of identified vulnerabilities, and the only way to do this is to change the python base image Meltano is built on.  


### Proposal
Having come across this article, https://snyk.io/blog/best-practices-containerizing-python-docker/, they appear to recommend alternative base images for Python. For example I am building a Meltano Python 3.8 Image, the recommendation is
python:3.8.12-slim-bullseye
I'm wonder if it is possible to have alternative Meltano Docker builds which I could pull with a more hardened base image?

I have tested and use the slim-bullseye by making my own Custom Meltano Base image and it seems to work well. The other advantage is that it reduces the size of the overall Docker Image.

Please Note: I really don't want to maintain my own custom meltano base image as I need to update a number of the other dependency files e.g. pyproject.toml. This makes my builds brittle and subject to build failure when there are updated Meltano releases.


### What does success look like, and how can we measure that?
Success for me would be less security vunerabilities.

I feel this could be done either one of two ways which aligns to @aaronsteers thinking as well.

1. Completely swap out the Python Base image with the slim Python versions as suggested by the Synk article.
2. Have alternative builds / variants Meltano Docker Images which use the slim Python image for the Meltano Base build.

### Regression test
(Ensure the feature doesn't cause any regressions)
- [ ] Regression build some Meltano Docker images to ensure TAPS and TARGETS still work
- [ ] Consider a phased deployed e.g. Option 2 first and then Option 1. In that way users can confirm the new slim python builds work for them.

### Links / references

https://snyk.io/blog/best-practices-containerizing-python-docker/

The attached file is my example [Dockerfile](/uploads/435de894cd04eef11959b31a7b3c7a4d/Dockerfile) for my custom based build of the Meltano Base using a slim-python base image.

record.title: Allow mappings to be "locally scoped" to specific extractors and loaders
record.description:
Currently all mappings are globally scoped. Meaning, if we want to define a `remove-pii` mapping for both `tap-shopify` and `tap-gitlab`, then we'll need to define them in a way to avoid name collision: probably `remove-shopify-pii` and `remove-gitlab-pii`. 

<details><summary>Click to expand example: defining mappers and mappings globally</summary>

```yaml
  mappers:
  - name: transform-field
    namespace: pipelinewise_transform_field
    pip_url: pipelinewise-transform-field
    executable: transform-field
    mappings:
    - name: hide-gitlab-secrets
      config:
        transformations:
          - field_id: "author_email"
            tap_stream_name: "commits"
            type: "MASK-HIDDEN"
          - field_id: "committer_email"
            tap_stream_name: "commits"
            type: "MASK-HIDDEN"
    - name: fix-names
      config:
        transformations:
          - field_id: "given_name"
            tap_stream_name: "users"
            type: "lowercase"
```

</details>

- If a user creates a mapping called `remove-pii` but accidentally applies it to the wrong tap, then it likely will fail or (worse) not filter or change any records at all, causing incorrect/prohibited data to land in the target.
- If the system detects two mappings are both called `remove-pii`, then the proper behavior is to fail before executing so that the user can resolve the naming conflict.

## Context-aware application of the correct mapping

Our initial long-term goal was to support locally-scoped mappings to that `remove-pii` could be declared locally as a mapping for `tap-shopify` and `tap-gitlab` (for instance), and each would be defined according to the needs of that extractor. 

## 'Optional' vs 'Always On' Mappings

With locally-scoped mappings, some mappings could be defined as 'always on' for a given extractor and others as 'optional', depending upon settings set within the mapping config.

For example, `remove-pii` could be 'Always on' and `ten-percent-sample` or `southwest-region-only` could be 'optional', and applied only when explicitly requested.

Side note: As a best practice, it probably makes sense to tie mappings to specific environments, so that each environment _always_ uses the same mappings.

## Avoiding accidental mismatch

In this case, if a third `tap-github` extractor is invoked with `remove-pii`, but there's no locally-defined definition, Meltano will know to abort and fail, rather than use a mapper scoped/configured for another extractor.

## Sample definitions inline with the tap/target

Because locally-scoped mappings are specific to a single tap or target, their definition is most intuitively configured alongside the tap or target definition, as child to it. 

Hence, our original spec from #2299:

<details><summary>Click to expand sample code</summary>

```yaml
mappers:
- name: meltano-map-transform
  pip_url: meltano-map-transform
- name: pipelinewise-transform-field
  pip_url: pipelinewise-transform-field
- name: no-activate-version.      # A fictional mapper that removes ACTIVATE_VERSION messages
  pip_url: no-activate-version
extractors:
- name: tap-gitlab
  # ...
  mappings:
  - name: pii-hasher               # The name of the map transform to apply.
    mapper: meltano-map-transform  # The mapper plugin to use.
    config:                        # What will be sent to the transformer in a config.json file.
      stream_maps:
        customers:
          id_hashed: md5(record['id'])
          id: None
loaders:
- name: target-salesforce
  # ...
  mappings:
  - name: add-global-guid          # The name of the map transform to apply.
    mapper: meltano-map-transform  # The mapper plugin to use.
    config:                        # What will be sent to the transformer in a config.json file.
      stream_maps:
        customers:
          guid: md5(record['id'])
- name: target-csv
  # ...
  mappings:
  - name: flatten-records          # The name of the map transform to apply.
    mapper: meltano-map-transform  # The mapper plugin to use.
    default: true                  # Transform prepended automatically if default=true.
    config:                        # What will be sent to the transformer in a config.json file.
      flatten_records: true
  - name: compat-fix               # The name of the map transform to apply.
    mapper: no-activate-version    # The mapper plugin to use.
                                   # config is omitted if the generic config is sufficient
```

</details>

In this example, the `mappings` collection can exist under any tap or target, and each mapping has:

1. `name` (what to call the mapping when invoked)
2. `default` (true or false whether this is applied by default)
2. `config` (whatever settings values are needed to configure the specific mapping)
3. `mapper` (a pointer to the plugin name that drives the transformation)

record.title: Consider global top-level mappings or mappers without nesting.
record.description:
Raised as part of #3273, we're discussing if we should declare mappings as singletons, each defined as its own plugin with only one mapping definition. Currently mappings belong to a mapper plugin definition, and each mapper plugin can have any arbitrary number of named mappings.

If we move to top-level mapper/mappings, then we would use `inherit_from` to reduce redundancies such as pip_url, etc., rather than having all mappings being nested under the mapper, and only the mapper technically has a pip_url and other plugin-level attributes.

record.title: ADR - Require environment for any invocation
Consider adopting an ADR process
record.description:
It could be useful to track [architectural decisions](https://cognitect.com/blog/2011/11/15/documenting-architecture-decisions) related to the meltano codebase itself and how they've changed over time. To track these down today you have to find the appropriate Issue/MR/Office Hours discussion. In the past I've done this via an ADR (and Architectural Decision Record). Records just live as markdown alongside your code (in a /adr or /docs/adr dir), and can be managed with something like https://github.com/marouni/adr (a small cli for creating new entries).

Here's an example of an ADR entry from the [adr-tools repo itself](https://github.com/npryce/adr-tools/blob/master/doc/adr/0008-use-iso-8601-format-for-dates.md):


```
# 8. Use ISO 8601 Format for Dates

Date: 2017-02-21

## Status

Accepted

## Context

`adr-tools` seeks to communicate the history of architectural decisions of a
project.  An important component of the history is the time at which a decision
was made.

To communicate effectively, `adr-tools` should present information as
unambiguously as possible.  That means that culture-neutral data formats should
be preferred over culture-specific formats.

Existing `adr-tools` deployments format  dates as `dd/mm/yyyy` by default.  That
formatting is common formatting in the United Kingdom (where the `adr-tools`
project was originally written), but is easily confused with the `mm/dd/yyyy`
format preferred in the United States.

The default date format may be overridden by setting `ADR_DATE` in `config.sh`.

## Decision

`adr-tools` will use the ISO 8601 format for dates:  `yyyy-mm-dd`

## Consequences

Dates are displayed in a standard, culture-neutral format.

The UK-style and ISO 8601 formats can be distinguished by their separator
character.  The UK-style dates used a slash (`/`), while the ISO dates use a
hyphen (`-`).

Prior to this decision, `adr-tools` was deployed using the UK format for dates.
After adopting the ISO 8601 format, existing deployments of `adr-tools` must do
one of the following:

 * Accept mixed formatting of dates within their documentation library.
 * Update existing documents to use ISO 8601 dates by running `adr upgrade-repository`

```


I think it could help in scenarios like https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/issues/3273#note_851602587 where there was a lot of discussion around the spec but it wasn't always captured or clear why certain decisions were made. It would also help codify certain decisions. For example, today we, unfortunately, have a lot of "logic" that lives at the cli parsing layer. Logic that should be pushed down into meltano.core. So we might want to codify that which I'd kick off with an MR adding this entry:


```
# https://github.com/npryce/adr-tools/blob/master/doc/adr/0008-use-iso-8601-format-for-dates.md

# 8. cli layer should hold minimal logic for accomplishing actions

Date: 2022-02-21

## Status

Proposed

## Context

The `meltano.core.cli` layer today in many cases holds much more logic than it should. In some cases the main application logic or
a core component is held at the cli layer. 

<some examples of bad use and good use>

To encourage clean code, efficient code reuse, and allow for the growth of our API layer all core application logic should be contained in modules and services
outside of the `meltano.core.cli` layer.

## Decision

The `meltano.core.cli` layer will hold only the logic necessary for the `meltano` command to parse its invocation/setup its execution
environment, and then use backend modules and services to perform the actual tasks. 

## Consequences

Core application logic is held in modules and services in blah blah.

The cli, API, and users can leverage the modules and services without having to reproduce
complex logic to support invocation.

Prior to this decision, some cli commands held extra logic:

 * meltano.core.cli.config
 * meltano.core.cli.install
 ...

We'll migrate/refactor these as needed, but it is expected that all new commands adhere to this ADR. 
```

With the status being either being updated to Rejected or Accepted and then merged after discussion.

record.description:
During one of the early review cycles for the stream maps MR we realized we'd forgotten to spec `meltano config` for mappers. So wanted to circle back and talk about that /cc @aaronsteers @tayloramurphy 

### List/set/reset/unset

At the moment configuring mappers is totally manual, but we should consider supporting manipulating mapping's config opts via:

1. `meltano config <mapper name>`
2. `meltano config <mapping name>` 

There's some issues with either path.

For the first, it's probably the route folks would expect to take when first installing a mapper - but also a bit weird as when invoking it, you'll be instead using the `mapping name`. Things like listing's might also work a bit unexpected. Do we list the config opts of the mapper itself, the config for all the existing mappings, or both? 

The second makes a lot of sense but seems problematic and addresses some of the issues of th first. Its biggest drawback would be around adding a new mapping. How would we know what mapper is being referenced when dealing with a not yet defined mapping? 


### Test

@aaronsteers @tayloramurphy not how we want to handle config tests for mappers/mappings - is there any special handling that would be useful? Or is parity good enough?

record.title: Flake8 --diff not working as expected from forks
record.description:
Following from the latest on community-contributed MR !2540, it seems the default branch targeting implemented in !2543 is not working as expected from a fork. Rather than compare `upstream/master` with `forkname/branchname`, the pipeline seems to be comparing `forkname/master` with `forkname/branchname`.

```
$ git fetch origin $CI_DEFAULT_BRANCH; # collapsed multi-line command
From https://gitlab.com/vischous/meltano
 * branch                master     -> FETCH_HEAD
Comparing to master
$ declare FILES=$(git diff --name-only ${CI_COMMIT_SHA} $REF | grep "\.py$")
$ if [ -n "${FILES}" ]; then # collapsed multi-line command
Changed files are\nsrc/meltano/__init__.py
src/meltano/api/app.py
src/meltano/api/controllers/orchestrations.py
src/meltano/api/security/forms.py
src/meltano/cli/__init__.py
src/meltano/cli/add.py
src/meltano/cli/cli.py
...
```

To resolve this, we probably need to somehow explicitly compare with `upstream/master` or a similar reference, and to do so in a way that also works on the main `meltano` repo, which would not have an `upstream` reference.

Cc @edgarrmondragon, @pandemicsyn

record.title: Freeze Gitlab docker images as stable, rather than continually updating
record.description:
Blocks https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/merge_requests/2542

Before we can direct users to leverage our Gitlab-hosted docker images, we need to resolve a potential issue where `latest*` and `v1.xx.0*` images are apparently being constantly updated on every build to `master`.

Probably the solution is to have a more clear delineation between which images are "dev/test" images needed by later CI steps, and which images are "published/stable" images that can be relied upon by users with production workloads.

Notes:

- We can _optionally_ keep `latest` and `latest*` images linked to master CI builds, with the proper caveat/disclaimer to users that they are non-stable releases for the purposes of previewing unreleased features. (Not for production workloads.)
- Versioned images `*v1.xx.0*` should definitely not be updated continually with new `master` updates. The timestamp on those images reflects them being continually updated as of now.

### Problem to solve
(Summarize the problem we are trying to solve in the form of we need to do [A], so that [B] can [C])

Early failure any Meltano task if the installed version does not fall in the supported range.

### Target audience
(For whom are we doing this? Include a persona)

Teams sharing a Meltano project.

### Further details
(Include use cases, benefits, and/or goals)

With new features being added to Meltano and the evolving schema of `meltano.yml`, it'd help in collaboration by hard-failing execution if the version of Meltano does not fall in the required range.

### Proposal
(How are we going to solve the problem? Try to include the user journey)

Similar to dbt's [`require-dbt-version`](https://docs.getdbt.com/reference/project-configs/require-dbt-version/).

```yaml
# meltano.yml
require-meltano-version: <string or array>
```

with the possibilities being:

* `"1.96.0"`

* `[">1.96.0, <2.0.0"]`

[//]: # (NOTE: This Release template is for Admin-Use only. If you've reached this template in error, please select another template from the list.)

## Evergreen Releases - Prep Steps:

An `Evergreen` release process means we are _always_ releasing. We open a new release ticket as soon as we've completed the prior release. (It's therefore the final step in this checklist.)

## "Evergreen Prep" Checklist

- [x] Open this Issue
- [ ] Indicate the version to be released here in the issue's title `Release vX.Y.Z`
    - If the release number changes (from minor to major or patch, for instance), update the version here and in the issue description.

### Readiness Checklist:

`Engineering` team, to get ready for the upcoming release:

1. [ ] Ensure any [already-merged commits](https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/commits/master) since the last release have [Changelog](https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/blob/master/CHANGELOG.md) entries (excepting non-user-impacting commits, such as docs fixes).
2. [ ] Create a comment in the `#engineering-team` slack channel with pending-but-not-merged MRs, potentially shipping. (Aka, the "burndown" list.)
    - Otherwise a comment that all known merge candidates are already merged.
3. [ ] Create or link to a summary of MRs merged and/or expected in the `#marketing` Slack channel, with an `@channel` mention.

### Release Checklist

Rotating `assignee`, on the morning of the release:

1. [ ] Changelog updates and version bump:
    1. [ ] Check the [pending MRs](https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/merge_requests?sort=updated_desc) to make sure nothing expected is still waiting to be merged.
    2. [ ] Create a [new branch](https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/branches/new) named `release/vX.Y.Z` and a corresponding MR with the `Release` MR template.
    3. An automated pipeline (linked to the branch prefix `release/v*`) will
    immediately and automatically bump the version and flush the changelog.
        - [ ] Check this box to confirm the automated changelog flush and version bump are correct.
        - You _do not_ need to wait for the CI pipeline. (An identical CI pipeline is already included in the below.)
2. [ ] [Cut a release tag](https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/tags/new) from your `release/vX.Y.Z` branch _(not from `main`)_ named `vX.Y.Z` with Message=`Release vX.Y.Z`
    1. In response to new tag creation, these steps are performed automatically in Gitlab pipelines:
        1. Abort if tag `vX.Y.Z` does not match output from `poetry version --short`
        2. Test _everything_.
        3. Publish to PyPi <!-- Meltano-only: and Docker -->.
    2. Validate publish once the pipeline finishes. (While the process is running, you can continue with next steps, such as changelog grooming.)
        1. [ ] Check this box when the tag's [pipeline](https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/pipelines) has completed (eta 40-60 minutes).
        2. [ ] Check this box when [PyPi publish](https://pypi.org/project/meltano/#history) is confirmed.
        <!-- Meltano-only: 5. [ ] Check this box when [Docker publish]() is confirmed. -->
3. Groom the changelog:
    1. [ ] Compare the [Changelog](https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/blob/master/CHANGELOG.md) against the `main` branch [commit history](https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/commits/master) and add any significant user-impacting updates (excluding docs and website updates, for instance).
    3. [ ] Review the Changelog for readability and typoes, committing fixes or updates if needed.
    2. [ ] Final changelog review:
        - Open the Changelog in preview mode, mouse over each link and ensure tooltip descriptions match the resolved issue.
        - Check contributor profile links to make sure they are correct.
    3. [ ] Merge the resulting MR to `main` with the merge commit message `Release vX.Y.Z`
    4. [ ] [Open the next `Release` issue](https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/issues/new?issue) using the `Release` template.

### Announcements, Marketing, and Promotion

`Marketing` or `Product` team:

1. [ ] Post-release announcement steps:
    1. [ ] Post announcement to Meltano slack: `#announcements`
    <!-- SDK only: 2. [ ] Cross-post (share) to `#sdk` -->
    3. Copy-paste to:

    4. [ ] Blog post
    5. [ ] Tweet the blog post

record.title: Consider defaulting `dbt_project.yml` to the root of project
record.description:
Note: This actually would be a change in `files-dbt` (or their replacements in #3105), but logging here for visibility in the main Meltano project.

Currently, we treat dbt as if it is isolated to the `transform` subdirectory but this has some disadvantages: (1) tools that expect `.dbt` in a certain location will occasionally not be able to locate those resources, and (2) the aspects of dbt that correspond to upstream and downstream mappings (specifically source definitions and BI report or "exposure" registrations) unnaturally confined to the "transform" folder rather than being defined adjacently with the other related resources.

As teams mature and divide efforts, a "shadow folder structure" starts to appear in parallel on the two subfolders.

```
myproject
|- .meltano
|- extractors
   |- marketing
      # These get imported via meltano.yml `include_paths` feature:
      |- tap-salesforce.meltano.yml
      |- tap-pardot.meltano.yml
|- loaders
|- transform
   |- .dbt
   |- dbt_project.yml
   |- raw
      |- marketing
         # These are dbt's definition files for the respective data sources:
         |- salesforce.source.yml
         |- pardot.source.yml
   |- internal
   |- marts
      |- marketing
|- meltano.yml
```

Then, when Salesforce `select` rules are modified, for instance including a new table, the developer needs to remember to _also_ go into `transform/raw/marketing/salesforce.source.yml` and append a record for the newly included table(s).

Versus an inline, side-by-side approach:

```
myproject
|- .meltano
|- .dbt
|- sources
   |- marketing
      # The Meltano-specific and dbt-specific source definitions can coexist 
      # in the same top-level `sources` directory.
      |- tap-salesforce.meltano.yml  # <- This is the Salesforce definition for Meltano
      |- tap-salesforce.source.yml   # <- This is the Salesforce definition for dbt
      |- tap-pardot.meltano.yml
      |- tap-pardot.source.yml
|- loaders
|- transforms
   |- internal
   |- marts
      |- marketing
|- dbt_project.yml
|- meltano.yml
```

Rather than segregating the tools into subfolders per tool, the project becomes logically organized by function: "sources", "transforms", "analyses", etc. And the "analyses" folder, for instance, can contain BI reports as well as their registration information as a dbt exposure.

Note:

- Even with this change, users can still put _all_ of their definitions inside the `transforms` subdirectory, but they are not limited to _only_ having dbt resources there.
- Having meltano files side-by-side with their dbt counterparts, for instance with the `source.yml` files above alpha-sorting with and being otherwise adjacent to the meltano source definitions, allow a `CODEOWNERS` model where:
  - EL maintainers (data engineers and/or IT infosec) handle _both_ the maintenance of the Meltano EL definition and _also_ the registration of those sources in the dbt `source.yml` files.
  - Transform maintainers (generally analysts or analytic engineers) aren't necessarily code owners for source changes and source import rules.
- There's nothing technically stopping users from doing this on their existing projects, and I've done this on a prior Meltano project. It's just that by default our folder layout treats dbt as constrained to the `transforms` subfolder unless a user changes it - and users may be hesitant to do so.
- The expected location of `.dbt` is (was?) sometimes hard-coded by third party tools and expected at the root directory. It was a while back, but I ran into this issue with [VS Code Power User](https://github.com/innoverio/vscode-dbt-power-user) not finding my `.dbt` objects unless they were in the root folder. (TODO: confirm if this is still an issue in the latest versions.)

record.description:
This is based off the discussion in https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/issues/3242#note_844044166.

When running dbt we should print to the console the full command thats being executed so the user is more aware of any Meltano magic that might be happening. The example was `dbt:run` which appends `--models $DBT_MODELS` and rendered as `dbt run --models my_meltano_project` vs `dbt run` which is very similar but only renders to `dbt run`. Neither of these log anything to the console so it would be very easy to get confusing outcomes here.

Something like @aaronsteers suggested:

`Invoking dbt with 'dbt run --models my_meltano_project'...`

record.title: Nested values in array settings don't have environment variables expanded
record.description:
Related to #2366 

### What is the current *bug* behavior?

I was having trouble using environment variables in the `meltano.yml` file, and it seems they are only supported for top-level configuration options.

If I define `SOME_ENV_VAR=SOME_VALUE` in the `.env` file and I write this configuration yaml:
```yaml
plugins:
  extractors:
    - name: tap-spreadsheets-anywhere
      variant: ets
      pip_url: git+https://github.com/ets/tap-spreadsheets-anywhere.git
      config:
        test: $SOME_ENV_VAR
        tables:
          - path: $SOME_ENV_VAR
            name: my_table
```

Then this is the actual configuration used by meltano:
```
$ meltano config tap-spreadsheets-anywhere
{
  "tables": [
    {
      "path": "$SOME_ENV_VAR",
      "name": "my_table"
    }
  ],
  "test": "SOME_VALUE"
}
```

And the `tables.path` variable is not set.



### What is the expected *correct* behavior?

The environment variable `SOME_ENV_VAR` should expend to `SOME_VALUE` in the `tables` array as well, and we should have:
```
$ meltano config tap-spreadsheets-anywhere
{
  "tables": [
    {
      "path": "SOME_VALUE",
      "name": "my_table"
    }
  ],
  "test": "SOME_VALUE"
}
```

### Steps to reproduce

- add the configuration above in `meltano.yml`
- add the line `SOME_ENV_VAR=SOME_VALUE` to your `.env` file
- see the result with `meltano config tap-spreadsheets-anywhere`

record.title: Improve plugin command error message to clarify usage syntax
record.description:
Related to https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/issues/3237#note_840251651 where @kgpayne said:

>Due to our custom syntax for commands, using the executable name is going to be equally jarring when users get to executing `meltano invoke great_expectations:checkpoint`, which is not functionality of the `great_expectations` executable.

I had a recent experience that I could see tripping people up. I wanted to use `dbt docs generate` and `dbt docs serve` which are not supported as `dbt:x` syntax because its not listed in the [discovery.yml](https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/blob/master/src/meltano/core/bundle/discovery.yml#L3073). This does not work:

```
meltano invoke dbt:docs generate
```
So I was thinking about adding an extra command to the plugin config like `docs_generate` that runs `docs generate` under the hood but then I realized that this works:

```
meltano invoke dbt docs generate
```

I'm not sure this is a problem but with such a minor difference in syntax I could see it becoming confusing whether your running a meltano command or raw command directly to the package. On one hand its great to allow commands to pass through so all the functionality is preserved but on the other its not clear in what context the command is being run. Maybe just having a warning that a "pass through" command is being used would be helpful, idk but wanted to call it out.

record.title: Naming convention for plugins
record.description:
### Decision - 2022-02-11

Aim to eventually have consistent kebab casing where possible, aided by #3220+ in the future. For now, use `great_expectations` to keep the experience within the plugin more consistent. 

----

@tayloramurphy, @pnadolny13, @kgpayne 

We've had some in-depth discussion on plugin names over on #2454+.

I started with the question, basically:

> should we keep `kebab-case` for our all plugin names as our current definitions use?

In the case of `great_expectations`, the problem with using the kebab case is that instructions from the site cannot then be copy pasted with the `meltano invoke ` prefix -- unless/until we build #3220+ or a similar implementation where the actual text name of the plugin's `executable` would also serve as an alias for it. If we were more heavily using `commands` in this case, like `meltano invoke great-expectations:new-datasource`, then the differences would be enough to warrant the different syntax. However, in practice, and in the files bundle, I think we're pretty much exclusively invoking the plugin and sending subcommands along as args.

Stepping aside from the great_expectations use case, I can see a value for other plugins to have the simplicity of just using a `meltano invoke <executable_name> <args>` syntax and not worrying about the Meltano name. The simplest path to get this intuitive syntax is to just allow the plugin name to match the default executable name.

Path forward:

I think we can just make a call that we are okay using the canonical or executable name as written for the plugin name. I'm fine with this as long as its a considered decision. In future we'll have a mix of `snake_case` and `kabab-case` plugin names, and we'll remember we decided this in order to optimize the overall ease-of-use on the user side.

@tayloramurphy - Especially from the Product side, would love your thoughts here.

record.description:
Right now when you schedule a job via the CLI, no input validation of specified intervals is performed. We're reliant on the schedule validating the interval and then surfacing issues to the user some how:

```shell
(melty-3.8) ➜  run-dev2 meltano schedule gitlab-to-json-stuff4 tap-gitlab target-json "stuff"
Scheduled 'gitlab-to-json-stuff4' at stuff

(melty-3.8) ➜  run-dev2 meltano schedule list
[@daily] gitlab-to-json-daily: tap-gitlab → target-jsonl x transforms
[5 4 * * *] gitlab-to-json-stuff: tap-gitlab → target-jsonl x transforms
[*/5 4 * * *] gitlab-to-json-another: tap-gitlab → target-jsonl x transforms
[stuff] gitlab-to-json-stuff4: tap-gitlab → target-json x transforms
```

[In slack](https://meltano.slack.com/archives/CKHP6G5V4/p1644520257808579?thread_ts=1644519607.344569&cid=CKHP6G5V4) it was mentioned that this was initially an intentional choice since Airflow supports a few different formats. 

Looks like vanilla cron syntax validation might be acceptable:

- [Airflow expects](https://airflow.apache.org/docs/apache-airflow/1.10.1/scheduler.html#dag-runs) a standard cron syntax or *nix style cron alias (`*/5 * * * *`, or `@hourly`) , plus "none" and "@once".
- [Dagster expects](https://docs.dagster.io/concepts/partitions-schedules-sensors/schedules#a-basic-schedule) standard cron syntax.

@aaronsteers mentioned in slack that we could potentially start validating but supply a cli arg for folks to use if they want to skip validation on the meltano side and instead rely on the scheduler.

record.title: inherit_from doesnt reuse executable
record.description:
I don't know if theres a technical reason why we do this but when using the `inherit_from` feature a tap/target gets a full installation of the python package when installed. I'd like to use the feature to configure my connectors slightly differently depending on the source but my docker image size is growing very fast and [my GitLab CI jobs are failing](https://gitlab.com/meltano/squared/-/jobs/2075149483) because I ran out of disk space.

Can we just reuse the parents virtual environment instead of reinstalling? It should save on space and installation time. Additionally it might be helpful to flag plugins somehow as prod installable, like I dont need SqlFluff, permifrost, superset, Airflow, when packaging so I need to [install each explicitly](https://gitlab.com/meltano/squared/-/merge_requests/55/diffs).

Theres optimizations that I can do on my end to avoid this but I have 27 plugins with inherits which is a lot but I'm sure projects will start reaching this size especially with more plugins being added.

record.title: Refactor add/add_related logic from 'cli.add' and 'cli.utils' into ProjectAddService and update tests
record.description: Currently the implementation of `ProjectAddService` includes methods for `add()` and `add_related()` for adding plugins and their related file bundles. There is also related logic inside the `cli.add`, `cli.install` and `cli.utils` modules for calling `add()` and `add_related()` and combining outputs. This causes issues during testing (e.g. [when testing if file bundles are correctly added](https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/merge_requests/2524#note_837720122)), as the logic defined for `cli.add` cannot easily be exercised using the underlying service `add` and `add_related` methods. I propose we consolidate these methods and helper-functions onto the `ProjectAddService`, providing args to determine if related plugins should be installed (as is implemented at the CLI level).

record.title: This is a test.
How to invoke and observe a container from another ECS or EKS container (and/or consider a "runner" plugin type)
record.description:
This is intended to be a Research Assignment. I don't think we have an answer on this yet, and we likely would have to dedicate some time to resolve. If anyone already knows the answer(s) here, we may avoid having to dedicate time perform the research. :sweat_smile: 


### Background:

If we want Meltano to be able to support "prod" scenarios that launch new containers, we'll need a better understanding of the current capabilities and hurtles/challenges associated from launching a container from another container.

### Questions to answer:

1. From an ECS container, can we launch additional ECS containers and observe their output?
   1. If yes, what's the approach and general level-of-effort?
   2. In terms of observability, I think we'd at minimum need to see STDOUT and/or STDERR logs, whether the task is still running or stopped, etc.
1. Same question as above but for EKS instead of ECS.
1. Assuming a "yes" answer to either of the above, can this be done in a portable way? Either using a versatile 3rd party tool or library, or by standardizing on K8s interfaces and tools?

### Impact of research questions:

- If "no", and this is not a viable path (either impossible or if a solution is just too expensive/volatile), then we would _not_ expect `container_spec` #2205 to be portable and applicable to an already-running container in ECS or EKS.
- If "yes", and this is a viable path, then we would want to think about how `container_spec` could be made to run from an already-running container.

record.title: Consider `--all` and `--interactive` flags in `meltano config set ...`
record.description:
Based on recent discussions around the difficulties in knowing _which_ settings to configure when adding a new plugin, I had an idea to support an interactive mode for setting all or any settings values.

Something like...

```console
> meltano config dbt-snowflake set --all --interactive

You are now configuring the "dbt-snowflake" transformer plugin.
For help, please refer to plugin documentation: https://...

We will now step through each setting. Leave any entry blank to skip, 
or enter a new value. Password values will automatically be hidden 
from display for any settings of type 'password'.

Press Ctrl+C to cancel at any time.

Setting #1: project_dir
Description: The root dbt path.
Type: string
Default value: $MELTANO_PROJECT_ROOT/transform
Current value: (none)
New Value: _ 

(skipped)

....

Setting #7: snowflake_user
Description: The username to use in Snowflake authentication.
Type: string
Default value: (none)
Current value: (none)
New Value: snowflake_prod_user

Value saved successfully to meltano.yml!

Setting #8: snowflake_password
Description: The password to use in Snowflake authentication.
Type: password
Default value: $MELTANO_PROJECT_ROOT/transform
Current value: (none)
New Value: ********** 

Value saved successfully to Meltano System DB!

```

Notes:

- In theory we could have separate flags for `--all` and `--interactive`, where `--all` implies or requires `--interactive` but `--interactive` could also be used on single settings.
- In the above mock up, I used SystemDB as the storage for secrets, but this could have read "Value saved successfully to .env file!"
- In the above mockup, I used `******` to note the user entering their password. In reality, we probably would not echo "*", since doing so lets an observer know how many characters long the password is. (I think the `click` library has some default handling for this.)
- By using this method for passwords, the user can avoid the password getting logged into their terminal history.

record.title: Allow plugin names to be aliased
record.description:
As per [this discussion](https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/merge_requests/2517#note_834526396), not all plugin executables follow the Singer convention of using dash separators. e.g. `great_expectations` defined in the following way:

```yaml
  - name: great-expectations
    namespace: great_expectations
    pip_url: great_expectations
    executable: great_expectations
    settings:
      - name: ge_home
        value: $MELTANO_PROJECT_ROOT/utilities/great_expectations
        env: GE_HOME
```

produces this user experience:

![Screenshot_2022-02-07_at_12.43.13](/uploads/9f5a433c0b3aafb2e07450ef74e15c59/Screenshot_2022-02-07_at_12.43.13.png)

Allowing aliasing of the plugin name `great-expectations` to `great_expectations` (i.e. accepting either form) would improve the experience for users familiar with either convention.

```yaml
  - name: great-expectations
    # define alternate name by which the plugin can be invoked
    alias: great_expectations
    namespace: great_expectations
    pip_url: great_expectations
    executable: great_expectations
    settings:
      - name: ge_home
        value: $MELTANO_PROJECT_ROOT/utilities/great_expectations
        env: GE_HOME
```

record.title: Resolve ambiguity in current supported ways to set environment variables inside the plugin env via meltano.yml
record.description:
# Meltano Configuration

Configuration management is a central part of the value provided to users of Meltano. Intention:

> Meltano is responsible for managing the configuration of all of a project's plugins. It knows what settings are supported by each plugin, and how and when different types of plugins expect to be fed that configuration.

## Use Cases

### Discovery

Discovery is how Meltano "knows what settings are supported by each plugin, and how and when different types of plugins expect to be fed that configuration". This is done by:

- Defining the settings available/expected to be configured for a given plugin.
- Defining the environment variables available/expected to be configured for a given plugin via the `env` settings [key](https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/blob/master/schema/discovery.schema.json#L653).
- Defining default values for settings via the `value` [key](https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/blob/master/schema/discovery.schema.json#L598). Note, default values can contain templated string references to environment variables (e.g. `$MELTANO_PROJECT_ROOT/utilities/great_expectations`).
	- Which environment is `MELTANO_PROJECT_ROOT` expected to be in? The Meltano runtime or the plugin runtime? 🤯 
- Defining env var maps to predictable names via the `env_aliases` [key](https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/blob/master/schema/discovery.schema.json#L661) for reuse across types of plugins (now marked as deprecated 🤦‍♂️). (e.g. `TAP_POSTGRESS_HOST` > `PG_ADDRESS`).
- Defining settings aliases via the `aliases` [key](https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/blob/master/schema/discovery.schema.json#L581) as alternative names by which the setting can be configured in `meltano.yml` and the CLI. This is often done to 'prettify' or make uniform with other plugin variants (e.g. `postgres_host` > `host`). **Note:* Meltano does not currently look for env vars of the form `<plugin name>_<alias name>` by default (though sunch env vars can be specified as `env_aliases` manually), nor does it appear to check or warn of clashes as the result of settings referenced in multiple ways (by its `name`, `aliases` or `env_aliases`).

In addition to the behaviours implemented as part of discovery, Meltano has 2 other builtin mechanisms for handling/discovering settings:

- [Pipeline environment variables](https://docs.meltano.com/guide/integration#pipeline-environment-variables) define settings that are passed from the environment of one plugin to the next in a pipeline (e.g. `extractor>loader>transformer`).
- [Plugin extras](https://docs.meltano.com/guide/configuration#plugin-extras) define settings used to configure the behaviour of specific plugin types _before_ and _after_ 3rd party code is invoked. This works by passing `plugin_extra` settings for use by all subclasses of [`BasePlugin`](https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/blob/master/src/meltano/core/plugin/base.py#L246) (e.g. extras available to the [`SingerTap`](https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/blob/master/src/meltano/core/plugin/singer/tap.py#L104) allow users to [override](https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/blob/master/src/meltano/core/plugin/singer/tap.py#L302) the `catalog.json` path used during Tap invocation).

### Configuration

Configuration is how end-users populate discovered settings with their own values. Config is done by:

- Using the `meltano config ...` CLI and `meltano.yml` to configure the above settings by name.
- Using environment variables in the Meltano runtime to configure the above settings via a `<PLUGIN NAME>_<SETTING_NAME>` env var naming convention. Environment variables can either be `export`'d into the Meltano runtime or coded in a `.env` file automatically discovered by Meltano.
-  Using values stored in the Meltano [system database](https://docs.meltano.com/concepts/project#system-database) to configure settings by name (also available through the UI).
-  Using the `env:` key of the [environments](https://docs.meltano.com/concepts/environments) feature to inject arbitrary environment variables into a plugins environment. These env vars will also be passed to subsequent stages in a pipeline according to the [pipeline environment variables](https://docs.meltano.com/guide/integration#pipeline-environment-variables) feature.
	- How are duplicates/clashes handled?
-  Setting env vars in the Meltano runtime environment matching names specified in setting `env:` and `env_aliases:` discovery keys (that do not have to conform to the `<PLUGIN NAME>_<SETTING_NAME>` conventions) to inject values into the plugins environment. **Note:** this is now an undesired behaviour, as per [#2984](https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/issues/2984).
-  Referencing provided [pipeline environment variables](https://docs.meltano.com/guide/integration#pipeline-environment-variables) in plugin tools code (e.g. the [provided profiles.yml](https://gitlab.com/meltano/files-dbt/-/blob/master/bundle/transform/profile/profiles.yml))
-  Using `plugin_extras` to configure the pre and post invocation behaviours of plugins.
-  Mapping a setting to an environment variable by adding a `my_setting: ${MY_ENV_VAR}` mapping under the `config:` block in `meltano.yml` or via the CLI using `meltano config <plugin> set my_setting "${MY_ENV_VAR}"`.
	- Which environment is `MY_ENV_VAR` expected to be in? The Meltano runtime or the plugin runtime? 🤯 

## FAQ's

- What is the difference between `config` and `settings`?

	Settings are specified as part of plugin definitions for the purposes of discovery. Config is the mechanism by which the fields described as settings are populated with values.

	Whilst `settings` usually only appear in `discovery.yml`, custom plugins added in `meltano.yml` places `settings` and `config` in the same view, which is completely baffling.

- How does `config` specified in `meltano.yml` arrive in files inside a plugins runtime? e.g. Singers' `config.json` or dbts' `profiles.yml`?

	For Singer the `SingerPlugin` class `src/meltano/core/plugin/singer/base.py` has a method (decorated as a `before_configure` Hook) for [writing a valid config.json file]() and another for [removing the file after](). Config arrives via an instance of the `PluginSettingsService` instantiated with both project and plugin.
	
	For dbt (specifically `profiles.yml` the approach is slightly different. dbt supports the retrieval of env vars within its config files (using jinja templating syntax). Therefore we need only match the env vars specified in the [provided profiles.yml](https://gitlab.com/meltano/files-dbt/-/blob/master/bundle/transform/profile/profiles.yml) to those available inside the Transformers environment. To smooth over this injection of env vars, Meltano makes available all the env vars provided to the Loader available to the Transformer as well, as part of the [pipeline environment feature](https://docs.meltano.com/guide/integration#pipeline-environment-variables). Currently we prescribe env vars of the form `PG_*` in the file bundle, but any matching env var name could be used (e.g. `TARGET_POSTGRES_*` to match the Loader env var convention).

- How do we determine what `settings`, specified in discovery, should be environment variables vs. which should be injected into files?

	This is implemented using the `env:` and `env_aliases:` keys in `discovery.yml`. Details as per Douwes comment [here]:
	
	> The behaviour around `env` and `env_aliases` is implemented in [`SettingsService.setting_env_vars`](https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/blob/master/src/meltano/core/plugin/settings_service.py#L63), which takes a `for_writing` boolean (which is `False` by default). Writing here means writing into the plugin's execution env, not-writing means reading from Meltano's execution env to populate a setting (that may then be written into the plugin execution env later). That `for_writing` flag is passed to [`SettingDefinition.env_vars`](https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/blob/master/src/meltano/core/setting_definition.py#L174) as `include_custom`. Following the logic there shows that when reading from the env, only the auto generated `<prefix>_<name>` is checked, and when writing into the env, env and env_aliases are used as well. I think the logic is that we want Meltano users to always use `<prefix>_<name>` consistently, but the plugin itself may expect a different env var.
	
	This description does not appear to explain the case described by [#2984](https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/issues/2984), which sparked our efforts to deprecate `env:` and `env_aliases:` in the first place 🤷‍♂️

## Proposed Next Steps

- To resolve  [#2984](https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/issues/2984) I believe we should remove the ability of the `SettingsService` to retrieve for injection any env vars _other than_ those matching the `<plugin name>_<setting name>` convention from the Meltano runtime environment. This meets Douwes intent that:

	> we want Meltano users to always use `<prefix>_<name>` consistently, but the plugin itself may expect a different env var."

- Implement a check to determine if any arbitrary env vars configured in `environments.[].env` do not clash with `env:` and `env_aliases:` defined in discovery. Warn or error if clashes are found.

- Provide guidance/docs on the usage on `env:` and `env_aliases:` keys in discovery. AJ suggests:
	
	> General plugins vs Singer plugins: General plugins must get some of there config from env vars; Singer plugins should not need env vars - but some do. Following from this:

	> - It's a healthy pattern for General plugins to declare `env:` entries to pass along settings to the plugin context (but probably not `env_aliases:`).
	> - It's a discouraged pattern for Singer plugins to declare `env:` entries. (We'll support if needed, but we should keep an eye on them and this should be the exception rather than the rule.)
	> - To avoid confusion around which env entries are needed for Singer plugins to function - versus which are convenient aliases, I think we should remove `env_alias:` entries from Singer plugins, replacing them with env: entries and an explanatory comment with issue link perhaps.

### Description V1

Quick summary of recent findings:

1. `env_aliases` / `env` - These are the same functionally. (New info to everyone!) - these fit the description as recently added in the JSON Schema for `env:`:
    - > `An environment variable that will be initialized with the setting's value whenever the plugin is invoked. This is used to inject environment variables into the plugin's execution context. If the named environment variable is already defined at runtime, Meltano will use the passed value from context instead of the configured value.`
    - Essentially a two-way read and write to/from the env variable.
2. The `env_alias` and `env` entries also have a special role in seeding `dbt_profiles.yml`. Specifically `PG_ADDRESS`, etc. I think (to confirm?) this is part of the reason dbt cannot be run on its own: because if the target wasn't invoked, those settings don't exist.
3. Settings aliases - newly discovered! Similar to `env_aliases` but at the setting level.
    - To be confirmed: if these are compatible with env injection in the form `<PLUGIN_NAME>_<SETTING_ALIAS>`. More in #3209.
4. `config` vs `settings`: `settings` are the plugin definition (optionally with default values) and `config` is one project's settings values.
5. When a user wants to map a setting to an environment variable, the recommended way of doing so is probably to add a `my_setting: ${MY_ENV_VAR}` mapping under the `config:` block.
6. General plugins vs Singer plugins: General plugins _must_ get some of there config from env vars; Singer plugins should not need env vars - but some do. Following from this:
    - It's a healthy pattern for General plugins to declare `env:` entries to pass along settings to the plugin context (but probably not `env_aliases:`).
    - It's a discouraged pattern for Singer plugins to declare `env:` entries. (We'll support if needed, but we should keep an eye on them and this should be the exception rather than the rule.)
    - To avoid confusion around which env entries are needed for Singer plugins to function - versus which are convenient aliases, I think we should remove `env_alias:` entries from Singer plugins, replacing them with `env:` entries and an explanatory comment with issue link perhaps.

------------------------

As per office hours 2022/02/02, the current mechanism of declaring an environment variable to be populated within plugin `settings` using `env:` and `env_alias:` causes confusion to even experienced Meltano users.

From the jsonschema:

```json
"env": {
    "type": "string",
    "description": "An environment variable that will be initialized with the setting's value whenever the plugin is invoked. This is used to inject environment variables into the plugin's execution context. If the named environment variable is already defined at runtime, Meltano will use the passed value from context instead of the configured value.",
    "examples": [
        "DBT_PROFILES_DIR",
        "GE_HOME"
    ]
}

"env_aliases": {
    "type": "array",
    "description": "Deprecated. Use to delegate alternative environment variables for overriding this setting's value",
    "examples": [
        "TAP_ACCOUNT_ID",
        "TAP_ACCOUNT_IDENTIFIER"
    ],
    "items": {
        "type": "string"
    }
}
```

Specifically, from `env`,:

> If the named environment variable is already defined at runtime, Meltano will use the passed value from context instead of the configured value.

This causes unexpected behaviours for users not aware of this dual behaviour. We propose that, in stead of relying on `env:` for both purposes (sourcing values to inject _and_ determining the target env var name to inject into), we simply remove the sourcing behaviour. This would mean Meltano would no longer search its runtime environment for matching env var names to retrieve values, effectively making any settings with `env:` specified an "environment variable type setting" (as suggested by @tayloramurphy [here](https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/merge_requests/2505#note_829519083)). Sourcing of values would only be possible via the standard mechanisms; explicit `config:` or env vars in the Meltano runtime of the form `<plugin name>_<setting name>`.

`env_aliases` might be kept to allow one setting to be mapped to multiple env vars. E.g.

```yaml
settings:
- name: aws_profile
  env: AWS_PROFILE
  env_aliases: [AWS_DEFUALT_PROFILE]
```

or both could be replaced with an array-type `env_vars:` e.g.:

```yaml
settings:
- name: aws_profile
  env_vars: [AWS_PROFILE, AWS_DEFUALT_PROFILE]
```

It is also worth considering if these settings should be injected as keys in config files either. Not doing so would further increase the specificity of the settings function as "an environment variable created from a Meltano setting".

### Possible Challenges

- Users can also set environment variables directly using the `env:` key in the `--environment` feature. This produces two ways to achieve the same outcome, and may cause conflicts and confusion to users. This can be handled with a resolution order (preferring settings above environment variables) and/or by warning/erroring if the same env var is specified by the two methods.

record.title: Use "setting.aliases" as alternative to "env_alias"
record.description:
As raised today (`2022-02-02`) in office hours, there is a benefit to `env_aliases` in that they can be used to ease migration across forks of the same tap or target. ~~I wanted to propose, along the same vein, a `setting_alias` which would work as follows:~~ We have `settings.aliases` capability which in theory could work at a higher abstraction level:

- The alias would be referenceable in `meltano.yml` `config:` blocks instead of the original name.
- The alias could be used in env variable injection so that `TARGET_SNOWFLAKE_ACCOUNT` could be used in place of `TARGET_SNOWFLAKE_SNOWFLAKE_ACCOUNT`.
- If both alias and the original name are set, this would be interpreted as a conflict. A hard failure would be raised: e.g.: `The setting 'SNOWFLAKE_ACCOUNT' was provided along with its alias name 'ACCOUNT', which is not permitted. Please specify 'SNOWFLAKE_ACCOUNT' or 'ACCOUNT' but not both.`

### Caveats

- As we're trying to move towards getting most/all config info from the hub (reducing dependency), this could be in conflict with that direction.
- Ideally, this would live in the hub definitions, rather than in discovery.yml, for the above reason.

### Potential added benefit for user onboarding and switching between variants

There could be added benefit to aliases, in that certain cross-implementation representations could be implemented by Meltano (and other orchestrators) generically. Many taps have common config settings but are each subject to variations in naming.

Example config options which would make good candidates for generic and cross-implementation aliases:

- `account`
- `username`
- `password`
- `port`
- `auth_token`
- `refresh_token`
- `client_secret`
- `host`
- `s3_bucket`
- `hard_delete`
- `target_schema_name`
- `target_db_name`

If we allowed the Hub entry to declare any of these aliases/forms of settings in the hub metadata, then orchestrators could leverage this info, and also (back to one of the original benefits of `env_aliases`), users could swap between variants without having to fully rewrite their config - at least not for those core elements that variants would have in common.

### Benefits for dbt abstraction

Downstream tools like `dbt` generally need a small number of variables related to where the data will land. Having common aliases for these functionally-significant parameters would allow Meltano to inject values and/or read values from those important settings. So, for instance, Meltano could know which setting names have the aliases `target_schema_name` and `target_db_name`, then we can use that to pass the values along to dbt for identifying the source of a transformation.

record.title: Add a `service` plugin paradigm, centered around `up` and `down` commands and behaviors
record.description:
We've discussed in other issues how superset and other plugins might unify around a `ui` command which launches a process connected to the UI and then can be shut down by Meltano killing the process ID.

Another approach is to define an `up` and `down` lexicon for commands, which is more of a `service` paradigm. This fits better when the thing being launched is not a single process, but instead is a complex set of services, perhaps multiple invocations of containers using `docker-compose`.

Plugins and use cases which might use this paradigm:

- Jupyter: #2595+
- Superset: #2605+
- Postgres: Specifically, a local Meltano-managed Postgres DB, run in a container.
- Clickhouse: Locally hosted, per https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/issues/3125#note_801037835

Note: I don't know that adopting this up/down paradigm requires an entirely new plugin type, but I'd be open to it if `service` was to be its own plugin, and perhaps similar with a files bundle, it may be complimentary to utility plugins instead of defined by them.

### Differences between a `service` paradigm and a `command` paradigm

Commands:

- Run until canceled or until the job is complete.
- State is expected to be locally stored within the project folder, or within a separately managed service.

Services:

- `up` runs until the launch is confirmed successful.
- `down` runs until the shutdown is successful.
- State is expected to be locally stored in a volume or backend, likely separate from the project folder.

### Example with Superset `ui` versus `up` and `down`

If invoked as a `ui` command, we assume superset will store its state locally in files or remotely in an external volume or DB.

If invoked as a service with `up` and `down`, we assume there is important and possibly complex state that may or may not be represented in the project folder after execution. Extra steps are needed to export that state to another machine.

record.title: Task Orchestration != Task Implementation
record.description:
**Note:** this issue is a written record of thoughts and experiences to serve as background to specific proposals. It need not be read unless i) it is linked to and relevant to a specific proposal you are evaluating, or ii) you are especially curious about the nuances of data task implementation and have time to spend reading.

**tldr;** implementing Tasks within the frameworks offered by the major orchestrators has limitations, and Meltano can (and in the case of EL already does) provide a superior overall experience for implementing and distributing tasks as lightweight and standalone applications. The data world needs more and better standalone TasK SDK's, not more orchestrators.

## Problem Statement

Airflow (via `PythonOperator` and other subclasses of `BaseOperator`), [Prefect](https://docs.prefect.io/core/tutorial/02-etl-flow.html) (via `@task` decorated functions or `Task` subclasses, including those from the [Task Library](https://docs.prefect.io/core/task_library/overview.html#task-library-in-action)) and [Dagster](https://docs.dagster.io/concepts/ops-jobs-graphs/ops#defining-an-op) (via `@op`, including [Integrations Libraries](https://docs.dagster.io/integrations#libraries)) all encourage end-users to define both the _implementation_ of their Tasks as well as the _DAGs (workflows)_ that orchestrate those tasks directly within their respective frameworks (i.e. the same runtime). As described in [Task Orchestration != Task Execution](https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/issues/3193), this can be problematic for even small projects when Task decencies are incompatible, necessitating the use of Docker to isolate individual Task from each other.

However, whilst this works to solve dependency-tree issues, expressing Tasks in standalone Docker containers negates the benefits of the decorators and Task base classes included with the major Orchestrators. No general-purpose Task definition SDK has achieved broad adoption, nor is there yet a standalone Task 'app store' for reuse of common Tasks. Defining and containerising Tasks is left as an exercise for the end-user.

## Opportunity for Meltano

Meltano, following a similar approach to [Singer](https://www.singer.io) provides mechanisms (the Singer SDK, and Utilities) to define Tasks as simple, standalone applications that _install into their own runtime environments_ (currently `virtualenv`'s and system packages, with other environment types such as Docker planned) and are invoked by CLI. In effect, Meltano _is_ a Task definition framework with corresponding registry (MeltanoHub) and package manager (the Meltano Project CLI). In this way, Meltano too is "Unix-inspired" affording us an opportunity to become a 'general-purpose data task framework', with accompanying repository for community-ownership of common task definitions.

record.title: Task Orchestration != Task Execution
record.description:
**Note:** this issue is a written record of thoughts and experiences to serve as background to specific proposals. It need not be read unless i) it is linked to and relevant to a specific proposal you are evaluating, or ii) you are especially curious about the specifics of data task orchestration and execution and have time to spend reading. **tldr;** today we expect that to run data tasks at all in production, we need to deploy an 'orchestrator'. This need not be the case, and is even contrary to the intent and design of the data worlds most popular orchestrator - Airflow. We need more and better execution options, not more orchestrators. ## Historical Context I use Airflow as the base example for this issue as it is widely understood and also served as the inspiration for later orchestrators. In the 'Current State of the Art' section below I endeavour to cite similarities and differences from other popular orchestrators. Airflow, developed internally at AirBnb, was [announced and Open Sourced in June of 2015](https://medium.com/airbnb-engineering/airflow-a-workflow-management-platform-46318b977fd8) and has since become a core part of many organisations data infrastructure. From the very beginning Airflow was built to "author, schedule, and monitor data pipelines", but not _execute_ the tasks in those pipelines. Back in 2015 AirBnb highlighted the **Extensibility** of the Airflow tool, through the use of Hooks, Operators and Executors: > Hooks are defined as external systems abstraction and share a homogenous interface. Hooks use a centralized vault that abstracts host/port/login/password information and exposes methods to interact with these system. > > Operators leverage hooks to generate a certain type of task that become nodes in workflows when instantiated. All operators derive from BaseOperator and inherit a rich set of attributes and methods. > > Executors implement an interface that allow Airflow components (CLI, scheduler, web server) to run jobs jobs remotely. Airflow currently ships with a SequentialExecutor (for testing purposes), a threaded LocalExecutor, and a CeleryExecutor that leverages Celery, an excellent asynchronous task queue based on distributed message passing. We are also planning on sharing a YarnExecutor in the near future. Core to Airflows model then is an explicit design decision to "run jobs remotely" - to separate orchestration from execution. 9 months later, AirBnb shared details about how Airflow is used within their wider Data Infrastructure: ![airbnb_data_infrastructure](/uploads/6a16d1e3099c71a2ed3b9cd476c462e2/airbnb_data_infrastructure.png) > Scheduling of jobs happens through Airflow, a platform to programmatically author, schedule, and monitor data pipelines that can run jobs on Hive, Presto, Spark, MySQL, and more — note that we logically share Airflow across clusters, but physically the Airflow jobs run on the appropriate sets of clusters, machines, and workers. We built Airflow and open sourced it, as well. The Spark cluster is another processing tool favoured heavily by engineers and data scientists working on machine learning, and is useful for stream processing. The team who conceived of and built the first iterations of Airflow emphasise over and over that "we logically share Airflow across clusters, but physically the Airflow jobs run on the appropriate sets of clusters, machines, and workers." Fast forward a few years and it becomes clear this advice was not heeded. With convenient facilities to run arbitrary code within the Airflow execution environment (using the bulit-in `BashOperator` and `PythonOperator` operators, or by subclassing the `BaseOperator` directly), 1000's of companies not running AirBnb-scale workloads on Hive/Presto/Spark implemented their tasks directly in Airflow. Whilst convenient to begin with, this soon became problematic. Anyone working on an Airflow project created before 2019 is likely to have come across dependency tree and resource isolation issues that result from 'doing work' in Airflows execution environment: - **Dependency tree issues**: All 3 of the offending operators execute within the same environment as Airflow itself. This means that any task dependencies (e.g. Pandas, AWS SDK, other 3rd Party SaaS clients) must not conflict with each other _or Airflow_. I personally remember the AWS case being particularly painful, with many SDK's using various versions of `botocore` to interact with common AWS integration points such as S3. Meltano, with our creation and management of virtualenvs, goes some way in alleviating this pain point, however we don't directly address resource isolation. - **Resource isolation issues**: Another consequence of running arbitrary code and tasks within the same environment is the "noisy neighbours" effect. Airflows parallel execution strategy (when using the threaded `LocalExecutor` and the `CeleryExecutor`) is [optimistic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Optimistic_concurrency_control); Executors will execute tasks up to the configured `parallelism` (for `LocalExecutor`) or `worker_concurrency` (for `CeleryExecutor`) _without any additional control or consideration for resource consumption_. This core execution strategy is 'good enough' when job execution is offloaded onto "appropriate sets of clusters, machines, and workers"; all the workers are doing is polling an external job runner (such as Spark) to retrieve status and log information. However optimistic execution fails miserably when two Network-intensive (e.g. Extract-Load) or CPU-intensive (e.g. Transform) jobs are run concurrently directly on the Airflow workers. Jobs begin to hang or fail at random due to "transient" resource issues, affecting overall stability of users pipelines. In summary, managing dependency and resource constraints of arbitrary data tasks in Airflow is not easy _by design_, as these use cases (however common) fall outside of Airflows intended use as a "job scheduler" _not_ a "job runner". ## Current 'State of the Art' So how do people manage today? After a [concerted campaign](https://medium.com/bluecore-engineering/were-all-using-airflow-wrong-and-how-to-fix-it-a56f14cb0753) in the Airflow community to extricate tools from the Airflow environment, we have arrived at the `KubernetesPodOperator` (and equivalents for other managed Docker execution platforms such as the `EcsOperator`) as a Best Practice. This approach directs users to wrap tasks in separate Docker images and to launch them onto Docker-compatible clusters like Kubernetes or ECS using the provided operators. This solves the two problems stated above; dependency-isolation is managed using separate Docker images for each task (or task type), and Docker-compatible clusters have native constructs for specifying the resources required by those launched Dockerized tasks (CPU, memory, volume-mounts, secrets etc). Huzzah! This shift to 'Dockerizing' tasks for execution is so successful that it is supported out-of-the-box by all of the 'second wave' orchestrators:

Dagster

 [**Architecture**](https://docs.dagster.io/deployment/overview#architecture) ![dagster-deployment](/uploads/517d9ac50dac1d8056426017253ac152/dagster-deployment.jpg) [**Supported Executors**](https://docs.dagster.io/deployment/executors) Example executors include: - `in_process_executor`: Execution plan executes serially within the run worker itself. - `multiprocess_executor`: Each step executes within its own spawned process. Has configurable level of parallelism. - `dask_executor`: Executes each step within a dask task. - `celery_executor`: Executes each step within a celery task. - `docker_executor`: Executes each step within a Docker container. - `k8s_job_executor`: Executes each step within an ephemeral kubernetes pod. - `celery_k8s_job_executor`: Executes each step within a ephemeral kubernetes pod, using celery as a control plane for prioritization and queuing. - `celery_docker_executor`: Executes each step within a Docker container, using celery as a control plane for prioritization and queueing.

Prefect

 [**Architecture**](https://docs.prefect.io/orchestration/#architecture-overview) ![prefect_architecture_overview](/uploads/35ca1be920a714f6e7796f0dac66aa3e/prefect_architecture_overview.png) [**Supported Agents**](https://docs.prefect.io/orchestration/agents/overview.html#agent-types) Prefect supports several different agent types for deploying on different platforms. - `Local`: The Local Agent executes flow runs as local processes. - `Docker`: The Docker Agent executes flow runs in docker containers. - `Kubernetes`: The Kubernetes Agent executes flow runs as Kubernetes Jobs. - `GCP Vertex`: The Vertex Agent executes flow runs as Vertex Custom Jobs. - `AWS ECS`: The ECS Agent executes flow runs as AWS ECS tasks (on either ECS or Fargate).
## Limitations of the Current State Whilst new Dockerized execution patterns alleviate the issues of dependency tree and resource isolation issues of Airflows' past, they are not without their own challenges nor do they yet meet the aspirations of "jobs run on the appropriate sets of clusters, machines, and workers". - Cluster managers expose _centralised_ resources, a pattern that is adequate for deploying web services but that is often not fit for the distributed nature of the data world. Using a single cluster for all the tasks in a DAG assumes all of the external service dependencies (e.g. APIs, databases, filestores etc.) of each Task in that DAG are met. For even a simple ELT pipeline, this assumes source and target are both accessible on the same network as the cluster. In a world of microservices, multi-VPC and multi-Account architecture patterns, this is a fragile assumption, and when false it forces teams to build and maintain complex network bridges to provide centralised access to those disparate services. Whilst it is possible to run two different DAGs (or their equivalent in the newer orchestrators) on two separate clusters, it is not readily possible to run two separate Tasks in the same DAG on separate clusters, nor is it attractive to run multiple clusters (with all the overhead that entails). - Docker and available cluster management tooling (such as Kubernetes) can be a high price to pay for the benefits derived. It imposes a steep learning curve and administrative burden on data teams that is only partially mitigated by paid managed offerings. - Taking a direct dependency on a cluster manager for the execution of DAGs compromises the local development experience (even as containerisation makes it easier to test individual Tasks). To execute a DAG made of `KubernetesPodOperator` tasks locally you must have a Kuberentes cluster deployed and available locally, with resources (such as volumes, secrets etc.) closely matching the configuration in production. This is not a simple task to set up or maintain. - Whilst it is natural to build Spark apps in the Spark framework, for remote execution on a Spark cluster, expressing other kinds of Tasks in standalone Docker containers negates the benefits offered by Task definition decorators and base classes included with the major Orchestrators. No general-purpose Task definition SDK has achieved broad adoption, nor is there yet a standalone Task 'app store' for reuse of common Tasks. Defining and containerising Tasks is left as an exercise for the end-user. More on this in [Task Orchestration != Task Implementation](). ## Consequences for Meltano By wrapping an Orchestrator as a proxy for providing Execution (i.e. `meltano invoke airflow` for Airflow to call `meltano elt ...`), we inherit the limitations of that Orchestrator. However, if we acknowledge that Orchestration != Execution, we can choose to reverse the relationship by providing our own Execution paradigm for Orchestrators (current and future) to integrate with, providing a Task Execution Framework (rather than a Task Orchestration Framework) performing a function equivalent to Spark in the big-data ecosystem. This idea is proposed in [#3139](https://gitlab.com/meltano/meltano/-/issues/3139).

If you are submitting an issue with a tap, please include:

This is based on [this slack thread](https://meltano.slack.com/archives/C013EKWA2Q1/p1643388924407829).

### What is the current *bug* behavior?
_What is happening now?_

When I try to use the `test` feature with dbt I get a message saying:
`Command 'test_publish_hub' could not be found. File bundle 'dbt' does not define any commands.`. It looks like its iterating my plugins by name and getting to my file bundle named `dbt` before it gets to my transformer named `dbt`. If I remove the files bundle, my tests work. If I rename my files bundle I get errors.

```
  transformers:
  - name: dbt

  - name: dbt

```

### What is the expected *correct* behavior?
_What should be happening?_

The test feature shouldnt consider tests in the files plugin section. Maybe larger than that it might need to accept a plugin.plugin_name combo (i.e. meltano test transformer.dbt:test_123) if a project has multiple plugins with the same name.

_How one can reproduce the issue?_

Install dbt then add a command starting with the test prefix and run `meltano test dbt:test_name`.

record.title: Support for disabling elt.log creation
record.description:
The `meltano elt` command will naively write out a log file on every invocation, even in the presence of a logging.yaml config. The elt.log has no built-in support for log rotation/max size/etc and users may not even always be aware of its existence. In situations where disk space is limited, this could cause issues. 

Since we support custom log configs via logging.yaml now, we could give users an option to explicitly disable elt.log generation.

record.title: Change instructions to recommend pipx instead of manually-created virtual environments
record.description:
Before joining Meltano, I'd created !1960+ to recommend installations with pipx instead of pip and manually-generated virtual environments. This came up again today and (now that !2496+ is fixed), I'd like to revisit/resurrect the pipx-based install guidance.

## Why this matters

I think we lose people when we ask them to create their own virtual environments. Also - then anything installed into that virtual environment is unavailable until the environment is manually activated, which requires memorizing the path to the activation script, and the whole process is just more cumbersome than I'd like.

Pipx was directly created to solve this problem:

- Virtual environments are created automatically.
- Shims are installed automatically to PATH, so you never need to manually activate the environments.
- The syntax is the same to install and upgrade, except one character: `pip3 install meltano` -> `pipx install meltano`.

Cc @edgarrmondragon

record.title: Support combining environment variables
record.description:
I've had a couple use cases where I'd like to set different environment variables at different levels. For sensitive credentials I set them in the .env while non-sensitive environment specific settings (like schema_name) get set at the meltano.yml environment level.

The functionality I want is to be able to combine both sensitive and non-sensitive variables for use in a plugin as an environment variable. A use case is in the squared repo where we have an Athena connection string used in Great Expectations and Superset:

`awsathena+rest://[YOUR_AWS_KEY]:[YOUR_AWS_SECRET]@athena.us-east-2.amazonaws.com/[YOUR_SCHEMA_NAME]?s3_staging_dir=s3://[YOUR_S3_PATH]`

I want to be able to set the secret keys in my .env and the path and schema in my meltano.yml environment. Right now templating is supported in meltano.yml for config values using environment variables but for some plugins, especially utilities, configs arent useful and we need to be building environment variables that the utility can access. Templating doesnt seem to be supported at the `env` level underneath the `environment` key. So right now I can set secrets in the .env and non-sensitive variables at the `environment.env` level in meltano.yml but I have no way of blending the two to pass along to a plugin, so I end up building the connection string multiple times in the plugins vs defining it once.

Ideas: Add an `env` key to plugin configs that allows you to use templating to build a new environment variable at the plugin/environment level. Or...allow templating at the current `env` key level based on whats in your .env file.
